Lesson: Property Observers
Property observers observe and respond to changes in a property's value. They are called every time a property's value is set, even if the new value is the same as the property's current value.

Core Concepts:
1. willSet: Called just before the value is stored. Swift provides the new value as a constant named 'newValue'.
2. didSet: Called immediately after the new value is stored. Swift provides the old value as a constant named 'oldValue'.
3. Initialization: Observers are NOT called when a property is first initialized; they only trigger on subsequent assignments.

Example:
    var status: String = "Idle" {
        willSet { print("Changing to \(newValue)") }
        didSet { print("Changed from \(oldValue)") }
    }

Note: You can't use observers with computed properties (which use getters and setters instead).

solution:
struct Gauge {
    var pressure: Int {
        willSet {
            print("Will set to \(newValue)")
        }
        didSet {
            print("Did set from \(oldValue)")
        }
    }
}

var gauge = Gauge(pressure: 1)
gauge.pressure = 2

