lesson:
Lesson: Protocols as Types
You can use a protocol as a type in many places where you would use a concrete class or struct, such as in variable declarations or as parameter types in functions.

Core Concepts:
1. Polymorphism: Functions can accept any object that conforms to a protocol, regardless of its underlying concrete type.
2. Abstraction: This allows you to write code that interacts with behaviors rather than specific implementations.

Example:
    protocol Loggable {
        var message: String { get }
    }
    struct Event: Loggable {
        let message: String
    }
    func log(item: Loggable) { // Protocol used as parameter type
        print(item.message)
    }

Note: When using a protocol as a type, you can only access the properties and methods defined by that protocol.

solution:
func reportHeat(source: HeatSource) {
    print(source.heat)
}

let burner = Burner(heat: 1200)
reportHeat(source: burner)

