lesson:
Lesson: Protocol Extensions & Default Implementations
Protocol extensions allow you to provide default implementations for any method or computed property requirements of that protocol. Conforming types can then use these implementations without having to provide their own.

Core Concepts:
1. "Free" Functionality: Types that conform to the protocol automatically gain the default behavior.
2. Overriding: If a conforming type provides its own implementation of a default method, its implementation will be used instead.
3. The Separation Rule: Unlike some other languages, Swift protocol definitions cannot contain any code. You MUST use a protocol extension to provide default logic.

Example:
    protocol Greeter { var name: String { get } }
    extension Greeter {
        func greet() { print("Hello, \(name)!") }
    }
    struct Person: Greeter { let name: String }
    let p = Person(name: "Swift")
    p.greet() // "Hello, Swift!"

Note: This is the foundation of "Protocol-Oriented Programming" in Swift.

